As is tradition, we will introduce CaMPL with a ``Hello World!'' example program. The ``Hello World!'' example demonstrates communication between a process and the outside world using the {\tt Console} channel type. 

The following code snippet shows a CaMPL process named {\tt helloworld} printing {\tt ``Hello World!''} by sending the string as a message on a channel named {\tt console}. 
The {\tt console} channel has the type {\tt Console} which is a special channel type hard-coded in the compiler to connect the program to the terminal from which it is run.
\begin{center}
	\begin{varwidth}{\linewidth}
		\begin{verbatim}
			1. proc helloworld :: | Console => = 
			2.    | console => -> do
			3.        hput ConsolePut on console              
			4.        put "Hello World!" on console    -- sends message to the console        
			
			5.        hput ConsoleClose on console       
			6.        halt console                     -- closes console channel and halts               
		\end{verbatim}
	\end{varwidth}
\end{center}
The \tc{process} {\tt helloworld} communicates to an in-built printing process via a channel of type {\tt Console}. In CaMPL, concurrent types are \tc{(co)protocols}, the instantiations of which are called as \tc{channels}. The \tc{process command} \ttc{hput} may seem strange at the first sight --- read as `handle put',  it initiates a channel for a  communication session. \tc{Protocol handles} are analogous to session types. As indicated by their names, the \ttc{put} process command sends a message, and the \ttc{halt} process command halts the calling process.

The {\tt helloworld} process can be invoked by calling it in the main process, {\tt run}, and giving it the {\tt console} channel as follows:
\begin{center}
	\begin{varwidth}{\linewidth}
		\begin{verbatim}
			7. proc run = 
			8.    | console => -> 
			9          helloworld( | console => )  -- creates helloworld process
		\end{verbatim}
	\end{varwidth}
\end{center}

The channel to the console can only be created by the main process.

\section{Designing a simple database server}

We begin by designing a simple database server in which a client and a server will exchange one message each. 

